1DEVELOPING A PERSPECTIVE ON LEARNING0

22 We have described mini-worlds and microworlds as designed environments, limited domains of special focus intended to present powerful ideas through virtual experience.   We will now procede in a new direction from this original description in order to consider the knowledge developing within the mind as a consequence of computer experience.  We take guidance from two earlier studies done at the Logo Project.  The first study, The Progressive Construction of Mind, presents our framework for conceiving of learning.  The second, Pre-Readers' Concepts of the English Word, introduces empirical material and an ur-theory or proto-theory of how children learn to read.  We will deal with the relevant ideas of each in that order.

.twinch 5.5
1MICROWORLDS IN THE MIND0

221 We described computer microworlds earlier.  The cognitive structure built within the mind by the individual as a consequence of experience with such a computer microworld we have chosen to call microworlds as well.  (When confusion is possible, we will distinguish between them as computer microworlds and mental microworlds.)  Mental microworlds are described succinctly in The Progressive Construction of Mind (and more extensively - but not more clearly - in One Child's Learning).  The guidance we take from that work centers on three themes. First, structures of knowledge in the mind are disparate, i.e. separate and distinct, and many of them are "task-rooted" (this means the definition of their elements are based directly on an everyday recognition of what's what in the task domain).  Secondly, the genetic path of microworld formation is essential to know in describing learning (whether seen as the formation of a new microworld rooted in task experience or as the development of control over or correlation between task-rooted microworlds).  Finally[+ + + + this third theme is either weak in itself or poorly expressed + + +], we describe learning, in its everyday sense, as a gain in performance that results from some rather simple interactions of task rooted microworlds.  This framework gives us an unusual perspective for analyzing what is involved in learning the skills of the lexical language - i.e. reading and writing.  We see in the analytical task the need to distinguish kinds of experience in the natural world in response to which people build up mental microworlds whose interactions permit the emergence of "reading" and "writing".  

