222In its general sense, reflective thought is considered a characteristic of the mature mind.  In a more technical sense, Piaget and Inhelder have described the reflection upon one's practical knowledge as the basis of the formal patterns of thought they witness appearing in adolescence.  If learning depends upon thinking about, reflecting on, your doing, should we not expect reflection - or at least its precursors, whatever they might be - to be evident early in life ?  Consider the incidents reported in Lois Bloom's  landmark book, Language in the Crib, where an infant was overheard practicing the phoneme couples in sets corresponding to their differentiation on the basis of distinctive features (as described by Roman Jakobson).  Is this an example of "reflection" ? The question is difficult to answer definitively because the child could not speak in terms sufficiently meaningful that one could infer what she was thinking.  It has been my good fortune to discover (in an ongoing study) a series of incidents which permit a decisive answer to this question with a slightly older child.  In summary, they amount to this: the two year child, Peggy, learned  a knock-knock joke in such a way that she could only participate in the dialogue as the initiator of the joke, thus:
