     We described the vocal language earlier (in section _________) in general as if it were a uniform thing of nor major internal structure.  The distinction between the inclusive and atomic concepts of words - both witnessed within the context of the vocal langauge - suggests we should conceive of the vocal language as composed of at least two major components: the first, focussed on phrases as units of meaning ; the second, focussed on free (unbound) morphemes as units of meaning.  (The latter would include specifically the names of objects, actions and modifiers of both.)  What should we call these components ?  Does it pervert the senses which we have used the word "language" to call them languages ?  The phrasal and morphemic languages ?  The reason for wanting to do so is that the lexical language is a modal variation growing predominantly out of the morphemic language - and one perfected by the socially imposed condition that it relate to the phrasal language of everyday speech.

