1LEARNING THE LEXICAL LANGUAGE0

23   What does "lexical language" mean ?  Let us make an obvious distinction first, then procede to ask how real and/or profound it may be.  The spoken language comprises all that we can say and all that we can hear (and make sense of) and includes all those knowledge structures that are accessible only through its use.  The lexical language, to the extent that is is distinct from the spoken language, is comprised of all that we can write and all that we can read (and make sense of) and includes all those knowledge structures that are accessible only through its use.  This sort of parallel description is meant to suggest  that there is a parallelism and possible equality between the two languages of English. We do this to raise the issue of how separate are the two languages based of the different modes of communication, and how are they related.  Does the lexical language derive necessarily from the vocal ?  Or are the two separate in essential ways and communicating at some "high level".  Is the distinction real and profound or superficial ?

.twinch 5.5
1CONTRASTING THE VOCAL AND LEXICAL LANGAUGES0

231  The distinction between the cognitive structures supporting the vocal and lecxical languages is very real.  People used speech for at least tens of thousands of years before the invention of writing.  There can be no stronger evidence required to show how the vocal language is independt of the lexical.  But could the converse be true ?  Could it be that lexical languages can be independent of the spoken language ?  Although the cases are rare, specific examples surely establish that it can be.  Helen Keller's learning to communicate with a lexical language though born blind and deaf is the outstanding example.

       A further argument supporting the distinctness of the vocal and lexical languages s developmental.  Any parent can witness how the infants vocal language develops gradually in a cyclic pattern, discriminations being made in what is heard then appearing in what is spoken.  Consider this example from the ongoing study of Peggy's learning:
.ss
.indent 2
^^^We have been trying to get Peggy out of diapers.  She has thoroughly explored her little toilet, she has seen other people used the larger toilets for sometime, and she has even used her toilet successfully - but not always, and some days are worse than others.  Yesterday she was  running around the house with a bare bottom, pissing all over.  After about thirty such "accidents", when she stood over a puddle and informed her mother, Gretchen scolded her, "Shame on you !".  This morning, before others were up, Peggy repeated that section of conversation to herself in her crib: "I just pissed. (Then, in a loud voice) Shame on you."   Later in the day, this phrase was evident in her repertoire.  When Peggy commanded her sister to move off a place she considers her own, and Miriam did not, Peggy began tugging at her and said "Shame on you."  At supper, Peggy climbed in her brother's chair.  When he asked what she was doing and touched her head, she whacked him and sais "Shame on you".

