If we compare speaking with writing, we can notice that from the infant's birth the sounds he makes have a profound and immediate impact on the world around him.  By contrast, the effect of any scribbles he might produce are nil.  Because speaking has a power of its own, it can enter with listening as a significant element in the INTRA-MODAL CYCLE of learning which characterizes the acquisition of the vocal language.  A child might sense reading as something important to learn, perhaps it might appear as a skill equal in value to listening as a way of making sense of the civilized world, but within the mode of lexical expression, writing is an expressive skill so difficult of access and so feeble in application that most people never write anything when they can avoid doing so.  This imbalance of the language modes explains why the reading instruction has been  "piggybacking" on the vocal language for millenia.  The sense in which this is an expression of a technological constraint will be dealt with extensively below (+ + +be very clear about this pointer+ + +).  

     Let us admit that adults experience language as a unified experience in the mind.  Of course the lexical language makes extensive use of knowledge developed through the vocal language ( and we have just seen a way of understanding why the vocal language is the dominant of the couple).  But the issue remains: is the adult's experienced unity of language a consequence of the derivation of lexical knowledge from vocal language or a consequence of the  integration of robust and possibly distinct systems ?

